    "abstract": "<jats:p> This paper analyzes how bounded rationality affects monetary and fiscal policy via an empirically relevant enrichment of the New Keynesian model. It models agents\u2019 partial myopia toward distant atypical events using a new microfounded \u201ccognitive discounting\u201d parameter. Compared to the rational model, (i) there is no forward guidance puzzle; (ii) the Taylor principle changes: with passive monetary policy but enough myopia equilibria are determinate and economies stable; (iii) the zero lower bound is much less costly; (iv) price-level targeting is not optimal; (v) fiscal stimulus is effective; (vi) the model is \u201c neo-Fisherian\u201d in the long run, Keynesian in the short run. (JEL E12, E31, E43, E52, E62, E70) </jats:p>",
